Interview Follow-up Questions

              Think about these before our next discussion.

                Q1  :   Why can't the Two Pointer technique be applied directly to an unsorted array?
                
                Q2  :   Suppose the interviewer allows you to sort the array first.                
                        Would you now use Two Pointers?                
                        What would be the new time complexity?
                
                Q3  :   If the original indices must be returned, can you still sort the array?

                        Why or why not?

                Q4  :   Suppose the array contains duplicate values.                
                       Does the Two Pointer algorithm still work?
                
                      Example:     [1,2,2,3,4,5]
                      
                      Target:    4

                      Explain your reasoning.



                    Q1. Why can't Two Pointers be applied directly to an unsorted array?
                    L5 Answer
                    
                            "The Two Pointer technique relies on the array being ordered. 
                            In a sorted array, moving the left pointer to the right increases the value,
                            while moving the right pointer to the left decreases the value. 
                            This predictable behavior allows us to eliminate part of the search space. 
                            In an unsorted array, moving either pointer has no predictable effect 
                            on the sum, so we can't determine which direction to move."

                      ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

                  Q2. If we sort first, would you use Two Pointers?

  
                            Sorting an array generally takes:  O(n log n)                            
                            Then Two Pointers take:  O(n)
                            
                            Total:  O(n log n + n)

                            Simplified:
                            
                            O(n log n)
                  Interview Answer
                  
                                "Yes. If modifying the input is allowed, I would first sort the array in O(n log n) time and 
                                  then apply the Two Pointer technique in O(n). The overall time complexity becomes O(n log n), 
                                with the extra space depending on the sorting algorithm used."
                  
      

                  Q3. If original indices must be returned, can you still sort?
                  Your Answer  : No.
                  
                  Verdict : ✅ Correct.
                  
                  Excellent.  However...
                  
                  Google interviewer follow-up: "Are you sure?"

                Actually...   You can sort if you store the original indices.
                
                Example:

                      Instead of sorting:  [11,2,7,15]
                      
                      you sort pairs:   (value,index)

                          (2,1)                          
                          (7,2)                          
                          (11,0)                          
                          (15,3)
                          
                      Now Two Pointers still work. When you find the answer, you return the stored indices.
                          
               SO ANSWER IS :      
                   "If I sort the original array directly, I'll lose the mapping between values and their original indices. 
                    However, if sorting is permitted, I can instead sort value-index pairs. 
                    That preserves the original indices while still allowing the Two Pointer technique."

            This is a very common senior-level follow-up.
            
            Q4. Do duplicates break the algorithm?
          L5 Answer

                "Yes. The algorithm still works because it relies on the sorted order, not on the uniqueness of elements. 
                  Duplicate values don't affect the rule that moving the left pointer increases or maintains the current value, 
                  while moving the right pointer decreases or maintains it. Therefore, the correctness of the algorithm is preserved."


